enhancement:layout_car:use transparency to draw some map features (#879)     With the introduction of the multipolygon code we now have all the nice landuses in the map. However, in OSM there are some map features that are not mapped as multipolygon but just "above" the other landuses. Like poly_zoo, poly_theme_park or poly_airfield.   Current configuration causes them to be hidden by the landuses, as these are drawn after the above mentioned. OSM's Mapnik style solves the problem by drawing those feature transparent above the landuses.   This pull request does so for some map features as well causing the map to look way better.     If transparent drawing is not supported by the platform, this causes the mentioned polys to be drawn above the landuses, showing them, eventually hiding some landuse details underneath. But this looks even better than before too.     NOTE: Transparent drawing is known to work on: Qt5 (sailfish) and gtk.   NOTE: Transparent drawing is known NOT to work on SDL   Dont't know for all the others. Sombody might want to check Android? Remember #852 on comparing screenshots though.     * Fix: layout_car: draw map features transparent on top     Some map featuresa re usually not put into multipolygons, but simple   tagged "on top" of the others. So It's quite common for example to   tag "poly_airport" on top of the underlying other landuses inside the   airport. Move (some) of those elements on top of the polygon draw stack   and make them transparent. Looks way better on graphics that support   transparency. Not much is lost on those that don't.     * Fix: layout_car: differentiate meadow and farmland in color     * enhancement:layout-car:Make poly_barracks and poly_university transparent

Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)     * Fix crash bug #780     …at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.     If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen.     I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but   control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.     Fixes #780

Prevent multiple instances of the same job running concurrently.     There are rare corner cases where a Job could be preempted by the   JobScheduler and then be rescheduled before the preempted job finished   running. This could create weird race conditions with bad consequences.     To fix this, we create a fun locking system that prevents two jobs with   the same UUID from running at the same time.

Add compact information to view model     Added a view model with both after much back and forth. The problem is,   if you don't then you end up having to actually reload the data set   which is slow, because of the fact the only real cache of the data is   at the front-end (i.e. the paged adapter) so if we want to update it and   the adapter's data is changing we actually have to re-create it rather   than just re-display it. Whilst this solution is not necessarily the   most elegant, because there is information there that is not needed,   it's actually the cleanest way of doing the change without any loading /   lag.

That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen. Add simple benchmark & a test framework (#2022)     See #2019, #2020 and #2021 for failed attempts at using a benchmark framework. So, for now I'll just go with timing the results manually.     For trying this out:   - Backup your current account first, maybe there are some bugs in switching accounts.   - You can run benchmarks on either an emulated device or a real device. For better benchmark results, you should run the benchmark on a real device and make sure that the core is compiled in release mode.   - Disable animations on your device, otherwise the test may fail. (Developer options -> Window animation scale, Transition animation scale & Animatior duration scale -> set all three of them to 0x)   - In Android Studio: File -> Sync project with gradle files   - In Android Studio: Run -> Edit configurations -> `+` -> Android Instrumented test -> Either select a specific class or select "All in Module" -> OK -> Select your configuration in the toolbar -> Click on the green "run" button in the toolbar to run the tests     When the benchmark is done, you will get a result like `MEASURED RESULTS (Benchmark) - Going thorough all 10 chats: 11635,11207,11363,11352,11279,11183,11137,11145,11032,11057`, Paste `11635,11207,11363,11352,11279,11183,11137,11145,11032,11057` into a cell in a LibreOffice spreadsheet, do `Data -> Text to columns`, choose `,` as a separator, hit `OK`, and create a diagram.

Redesigned KanaQuestion classes     New Question class will be used as a generic abstract version of the KanaQuestion class, extended by the KanaQuestion and WordQuestion classes. I redesigned many classes so they use the Question class, instead of the KanaQuestion class. This makes it easier to predict certain app behaviour. Since the WordQuestion class needs to handle many things differently, it's simpler to just extend a generic class, rather than risk the KanaQuestion methods accidentally being triggered because I didn't override the methods properly. Also, the methods have been renamed to be no longer KanaQuestion specific, and therefore their function is clearer. I'm not quite done with this process. I still have to rename some things in the ReferenceCell class, and the 'options' and 'logs' packages. But for now, this is good.

Redesigned KanaQuestion classes     New Question class will be used as a generic abstract version of the KanaQuestion class, extended by the KanaQuestion and WordQuestion classes. I redesigned many classes so they use the Question class, instead of the KanaQuestion class. This makes it easier to predict certain app behaviour. Since the WordQuestion class needs to handle many things differently, it's simpler to just extend a generic class, rather than risk the KanaQuestion methods accidentally being triggered because I didn't override the methods properly. Also, the methods have been renamed to be no longer KanaQuestion specific, and therefore their function is clearer. I'm not quite done with this process. I still have to rename some things in the ReferenceCell class, and the 'options' and 'logs' packages. But for now, this is good.

Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)     * Fix crash bug #780     …at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.     If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen.     I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but   control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.     Fixes #780

Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)     * Fix crash bug #780     …at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.     If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen.     I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but   control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.     Fixes #780

Note: While it would be possible to allow the provider to work even from its own process, this is not considered good practice, so we keep it disabled on production builds until such time as it becomes explicitly required. Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)     * Fix crash bug #780     …at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.     If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen.     I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but   control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.     Fixes #780

Made sure the Known Location notification updated the PendingIntent.     It wasn't set to FLAG_UPDATE_CURRENT, meaning it had a chance of sending   bad data to CentralMap in admittedly rare circumstances (specifically,   if the user had locations in multiple graticules, got a notification in   one graticule on one day, then got another notification in another   graticule on a different day, and the old PendingIntent hadn't been   destroyed yet).

Don't Crash on Nullable ViewModels (#784)     * Fix crash bug #780     …at least for the case that I know how to reproduce.     If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen. Fix broken unit test (#720)     The unit test called a method that called onNext on a subject. This   subject was subscribed to as an observable to do some extra work, but   was doing this work on an io thread. The bug was that the unit test was   doing the checks before the code that was supposed to run on the io   thread ran (since the unit test itself is synchronous unless we   explicitly wait for something). The fix is to explicitly wait for the   observable to get an event, thereby letting us know that the code was   executed, before checking that the right things were called.

Allow users to adjust terminal transcript rows with termux.properties     This `terminal-transcript-rows` key can be used to adjust the terminal transcript rows. The user can set an integer value between `100` and `50000`. The default value is still `2000`. So adding an entry like `terminal-transcript-rows=10000` to `termux.properties` file will allow users to scroll back ~10000 lines of command output. After updating the value, termux must be restarted. You can also run `termux-reload-settings` command so that termux loads the updated value, but only new sessions will use the updated value, existing sessions will not be affected.     You can test this with the following, where `70` is number of `x` characters per line and `10001` is the number of lines to print.   `x="$(printf 'x%.0s' {1..70})"; for i in {1..10001}; do echo "$i:$x"; done`     Be advised that using large values may have a performance impact depending on your device capabilities, so use at your own risk.     Closes #2071

Time info hotfix and SummaryGraph bugfix      Commit f1bc4ed added the missing time info for active day multi ticks and made sure to only save the   time info for active day single ticks (and not for single ticks for past days). (NB: the first part of my commit   message of f1bc4ed was not accurate about this).   As a result of these changes an existing code error in the calculation of the number of days between two   dates became apparent: the number of days between two dates cannot be calculated by just dividing the   time difference in ms by the number of ms per day as it can be more or less than 24 hrs for two days in   a row with time info attached.   This hotfix removes the time info from the dates before day difference calculation. It's rather ugly and will   be replaced by a nicer solution later.      The change in SummaryGraph fixes a bug introduced with b855ba7 that prevents empty streaks and   weekday graphs from being shown.

Ignore exception when starting warm-up service for Custom Tabs     Some more details (see also the source code comment). The reason why   this exception occurs is probably as follows. On Android 8 and above,   an app can no longer start services when it is in the background.   However, to warm the Custom Tabs, a service has to be started. There is   a very small but real possibility that the user opens an activity with   custom tabs and navigates away from the app after the connection has   been initialized, but before the actual warm-up service has started.   This theory is supported by the crash logs which only indicate   Android 8+, and various only bug reports.     See also e.g. https://github.com/openid/AppAuth-Android/issues/425

This is a very hacky approach that uses View.OnAttachStateChangeListener to   attempt to restore the saved bundle values after databinding has reset them   to the Link model. Saving the values to the Link model directly during   onSaveInstanceState might be problematic since the user might not want to save   the draft changes.     Need to look into a cleaner approach, but this should be sufficient since   EditLinkActivity isn't used much

Add simple benchmark & a test framework (#2022)     See #2019, #2020 and #2021 for failed attempts at using a benchmark framework. So, for now I'll just go with timing the results manually.     For trying this out:   - Backup your current account first, maybe there are some bugs in switching accounts.   - You can run benchmarks on either an emulated device or a real device. For better benchmark results, you should run the benchmark on a real device and make sure that the core is compiled in release mode.   - Disable animations on your device, otherwise the test may fail. (Developer options -> Window animation scale, Transition animation scale & Animatior duration scale -> set all three of them to 0x)   - In Android Studio: File -> Sync project with gradle files   - In Android Studio: Run -> Edit configurations -> `+` -> Android Instrumented test -> Either select a specific class or select "All in Module" -> OK -> Select your configuration in the toolbar -> Click on the green "run" button in the toolbar to run the tests     When the benchmark is done, you will get a result like `MEASURED RESULTS (Benchmark) - Going thorough all 10 chats: 11635,11207,11363,11352,11279,11183,11137,11145,11032,11057`, Paste `11635,11207,11363,11352,11279,11183,11137,11145,11032,11057` into a cell in a LibreOffice spreadsheet, do `Data -> Text to columns`, choose `,` as a separator, hit `OK`, and create a diagram.

Need to look into a cleaner approach, but this should be sufficient since   EditLinkActivity isn't used much

Fix broken unit test (#720)     The unit test called a method that called onNext on a subject. This   subject was subscribed to as an observable to do some extra work, but   was doing this work on an io thread. The bug was that the unit test was   doing the checks before the code that was supposed to run on the io   thread ran (since the unit test itself is synchronous unless we   explicitly wait for something). The fix is to explicitly wait for the   observable to get an event, thereby letting us know that the code was   executed, before checking that the right things were called.

Fix VR crash when sketch starts for some devices.     I could not reproduce this, but when targeting VR on Sara's (my mentor's) phone, the sketch crashed with a NoClassDefFoundError for the R.java for the Google VR library. Now AAPT builds R for the GVR library when VR is selected. It actually builds R for GVR instead of AppCompat, but this seems to be OK because AppCompat's R isn't used for VR sketches. (It is easier to implement it this way because Java arrays are fixed-length and I had difficulties getting AAPT to recognize the "--extra-packages" flag twice.)     Also add "processing.vr" to the list of ignorable imports when targeting VR. On the desktop, VR is packaged as a library, but for APDE we are not doing it this way because we want any 3D sketch to be runnable as a VR sketch.

If DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification.renderToViewModel() returns null,   viewing the Recent Notifications screen will crash.     The method is declared @Nullable. That’s inoperative (to use Nixon’s   euphemism for “lie”).     SummaryNotification.renderToViewModel() does return null without   causing a crash, but maybe some other code is careful to not add that   null to the view model list.     * Cope with a null ViewModel     ViewModelRenderer. renderToViewModel() is declared @Nullable, so cope   with nulls.     If not for the previous change that makes   DistrictPointsUpdatedNotification return a real ViewModel, each of that   kind of notification saved would trigger this case upon opening the   Recent Notifications screen.     I also put a check in RecentNotificationsListBinder to be safe, but   control doesn’t get there in this case. Perhaps it crashes before then.     Fixes #780
